WEBVTT

00:00:01.280 --> 00:00:05.920
<v Speaker 1>We said that the word for always was siembre.

00:00:05.920 --> 00:00:06.720
<v Speaker 2>Siempre.

00:00:06.960 --> 00:00:07.280
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:00:07.280 --> 00:00:14.960
<v Speaker 1>Now if you know Italian or some other Latin language, maybe you have something like sempre.

00:00:14.340 --> 00:00:19.940
<v Speaker 1>in that language and you can see again that the E is splitting between siempre and siempre.

00:00:19.940 --> 00:00:25.380
<v Speaker 1>So if you know one of these other languages or if you've studied them, it can be useful just to notice that.

00:00:25.380 --> 00:00:28.980
<v Speaker 1>And just noticing that helps you internalize this new word.

00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:35.000
<v Speaker 1>So for example, well in Spanish is bien, like in the beginning of welcome, bienvenido.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:37.240
<v Speaker 1>This in Italian is bene.

00:00:37.240 --> 00:00:41.720
<v Speaker 1>We see that we get rid of the E, last E, and the E in the middle splits.

00:00:41.540 --> 00:00:44.180
<v Speaker 1>You have in French, on for good.

00:00:44.180 --> 00:00:47.620
<v Speaker 1>What do you think good might be in Spanish?

00:00:47.620 --> 00:00:50.660
<v Speaker 1>What do you think we'll do to make that more Spanish?

00:00:50.660 --> 00:00:51.540
<v Speaker 1>Bueno.

00:00:51.540 --> 00:00:52.180
<v Speaker 1>Bueno

00:00:53.079 --> 00:01:00.039
<v Speaker 1>We also said that vamos, vamos meant we're going or let's go and it's something that you're gonna hear all the time.

00:01:00.039 --> 00:01:01.800
<v Speaker 1>Vamos, vamos, let's go

